    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA349-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu talaimakaṉ tōḻi kēṭpat taṉṉuḷḷē colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what HE said to his own heart so that the confidante would hear.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA349">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            kaṭuntē rēṟiyuṅ kāliṟ ceṉṟuṅ</l>
<l>            koṭuṅkaḻi maruṅki ṉaṭumpumalar koytuṅ</l>
<l>            kaitai tūkkiyu neytal kuṟṟum</l>
<l>            puṇarntām pōla vuṇarnta neñcamoṭu</l>
<l>            vaikalu miṉaiya mākavuñ ceytārp</l>
<l>            pacumpūṇ vēnta raḻinta pācaṟai</l>
<l>            yoḷiṟuvē laḻuvattuk kaḷiṟupaṭa poruta</l>
<l>            perumpuṇ ṇuṟunarkkup pēey pōlap</l>
<l>            piṉṉilai muṉiyā namvayi</l>
<l>            ṉeṉṉeṉa niṉaiyuṅkol paratavar makaḷē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent">            Mounting the quick chariot and going like the wind</l>
<l rend="indent">            and plucking Aṭumpu blossoms by the side of the curved backwaters</l>
<l rend="indent">            and lifting the [branches of] Kaitai and plucking blue waterlilies,</l>
<l rend="indent3">            with a heart that perceives [this] as if we were united,</l>
<l rend="indent2">            even if we [are] like this daily,</l>
<l>        will she think “what [is this],”</l>
<l rend="indent4">            the fishermen’s daughter,</l>
<l>            about us who are not averse to standing behind [her],</l>
<l rend="indent">            as the evil spirits<note place="foot">What can be the impact of this simile? Certainly HE is compared to the <term xml:lang="ta">pēey</term>, and T.V.G. ascertains that it means a benevolent spirit here that guards the wounded soldiers on the battlefield, but what we know from literature (especially the later one, but also <term xml:lang="ta">Puṟam</term>) is that the <term xml:lang="ta">pēey</term> are evil and corpse-eating spirits who feast on the battlefield. Does this voice his fear that he is merely embarrassing her?</note> for those who have big wounds</l>
<l rend="indent2">            beaten when the elephants came in a thicket of bright spears</l>
<l rend="indent3">            into the encampment ruined by the king with green ornaments</l>
<l rend="indent4">            [and] an artifical(?)<note place="foot">What can be the impact of <term xml:lang="ta">cey tār</term> here? A garland specially made for the occasion? A garland not made of flowers but of gems?</note> garland?</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
